    "conclusion": "Simple positive expert chunking is much slower than the large-batch compact-reduce path. The Python-level bucket16 count-bucket path passes correctness but is far slower because bucket index/copy overhead dominates. The existing AITER persistent and non-persistent grouped-GEMM backward paths and compact AITER fwd+bwd path pass small BF16 correctness but are slower in the full-layer S=2048 integration. Route build and gate-gradient removal only saves about 1.17 ms; the larger 6.12 ms learned-vs-fixed gap points to learned route imbalance/padded work or a need for a custom compact grouped GEMM/kernel path that preserves large-kernel efficiency without Python-side bucket materialization or current AITER overheads."
